{"questionId":"19850","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Consider the function&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mo>-</mo><mi>a</mi><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>a</mi></msqrt><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>a</mi><mo>∈</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℝ</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>For <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn></math> the curve <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>f</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;has a single local maximum.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find in terms of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi></math> the value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math> at which the maximum occurs.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>a</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>(M1)</strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>a</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong>A1</strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>[2 marks]</strong></p>","meta":{"questionId":"19850","referenceCode":"EXN.1.AHL.TZ0.15b","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Find in terms of a the value of x at which the maximum occurs.","paper":"1","level":"HL","questionNumber":"b","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 5—Calculus","Topic 5—Calculus","SL 5.6—Stationary points, local max and min","Topic 5—Calculus","AHL 5.9—Differentiating standard functions and derivative rules"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}